// ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
// 1. NOTE NAMES & OCTAVE NOTATION
// ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
//
// 7 natural notes:    c   d   e   f   g   a   b
// Sharps (raise ½):   cs  ds  fs  gs  as   (= Db Eb Gb Ab Bb enharmonically)
// Flats  (lower ½):   db  eb  gb  ab  bb
// Octave number:      c4 = middle C (261 Hz), c5 = one octave up
//
// FULL CHROMATIC SCALE (C4 to B4):
//   c4  cs4  d4  ds4  e4  f4  fs4  g4  gs4  a4  as4  b4
//
// OCTAVE REFERENCE:
//   c2  very low bass      (~65 Hz)
//   c3  low / bass range   (~131 Hz)
//   c4  middle C           (~262 Hz)
//   c5  upper mid / lead   (~523 Hz)
//   c6  high / bright      (~1047 Hz)

setcpm(30)
note("c4 d4 e4 f4 g4 a4 b4 c5").sound("piano")

// note("c2 c3 c4 c5").sound("sine")                  // octave comparison
// note("c4 cs4 d4 ds4 e4 f4 fs4 g4 gs4 a4 as4 b4") // chromatic scale
//   .sound("piano").slow(2)


// ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
// 2. THREE WAYS TO PLAY PITCH
// ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
//
//   note("c4 e4 g4")          → named notes, explicit pitch
//   note("c4 e4 g4").sound("piano")   → play on instrument
//
//   n("0 1 2 3").scale("C:major")     → scale degrees (0 = root)
//   n("0 1 2 3").scale("C:major").sound("piano")
//
//   s("piano").note("c4 e4 g4")       → sample triggered at pitch
//
//   Numbers in n():
//     0 = root (C4 in C:major)
//     1 = 2nd degree  (D4)
//     2 = 3rd degree  (E4)
//     4 = 5th degree  (G4)   ← stable
//     7 = root, octave up    (C5)
//    -1 = 7th below root     (B3)
//    -2 = 6th below root     (A3)
//     8 = 2nd degree, up octave (D5)

setcpm(30)

// --- note(): direct pitch name ---
note("c4 e4 g4 b4 g4 e4 c4 ~").sound("piano")

// --- n(): scale degrees — change key by changing one word ---
// n("0 2 4 7 4 2 0 ~").scale("C:major").sound("piano")
// n("0 2 4 7 4 2 0 ~").scale("A:minor").sound("piano")   // same pattern, different mood
// n("0 2 4 7 4 2 0 ~").scale("D:dorian").sound("piano")

// --- s() with .note(): sample pitched to note ---
// s("piano").note("c4 e4 g4")


// ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
// 3. SCALES — FULL REFERENCE
// ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
//
// Format:  n("degrees").scale("ROOT:name").sound("...")
// Change root by replacing the first part: "C:", "G:", "A:", "Bb:" etc.
//
//  SCALE NAME        DEGREES         CHARACTER
//  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//  major             1 2 3 4 5 6 7   bright, happy, resolved
//  minor             1 2 b3 4 5 b6 b7 dark, sad, emotional
//  dorian            1 2 b3 4 5 6 b7  jazzy minor (raised 6th)
//  phrygian          1 b2 b3 4 5 b6 b7 Spanish, flamenco, metal
//  lydian            1 2 3 #4 5 6 7   dreamy, floating (raised 4th)
//  mixolydian        1 2 3 4 5 6 b7   bluesy major (lowered 7th)
//  locrian           1 b2 b3 4 b5 b6 b7 dark, unstable, rarely used
//  pentatonic        1 2 3 5 6        pop/folk, always sounds good
//  minpentatonic     1 b3 4 5 b7      blues, rock, soul
//  blues             1 b3 4 b5 5 b7   classic blues sound
//  harmonicminor     1 2 b3 4 5 b6 7  dramatic, cinematic (raised 7th)
//  melodicminor      1 2 b3 4 5 6 7   jazz, sophisticated

setcpm(30)

// Play the same degree pattern through different scales — hear the character change:
n("0 2 4 3 2 4 0 ~").scale("C:major").sound("piano").slow(2)

// n("0 2 4 3 2 4 0 ~").scale("C:minor").sound("piano").slow(2)
// n("0 2 4 3 2 4 0 ~").scale("C:dorian").sound("piano").slow(2)
// n("0 2 4 3 2 4 0 ~").scale("C:blues").sound("piano").slow(2)
// n("0 2 4 3 2 4 0 ~").scale("C:phrygian").sound("piano").slow(2)
// n("0 2 4 3 2 4 0 ~").scale("C:pentatonic").sound("piano").slow(2)


// ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
// 4. CHORDS — SIMULTANEOUS NOTES WITH [ , ]
// ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
//
// Inside a note string, comma-separated notes inside [] play TOGETHER.
//   note("[c4, e4, g4]")         → C major triad
//   note("[c4, eb4, g4]")        → C minor triad (lowered 3rd)
//
// TRIAD FORMULAS (semitones from root):
//   major:      root + 4 + 3     → bright
//   minor:      root + 3 + 4     → dark
//   diminished: root + 3 + 3     → tense
//   augmented:  root + 4 + 4     → floating
//
// 7TH CHORDS (add one more note above the triad):
//   major 7:    [c4, e4, g4, b4]   → lush, jazzy
//   dominant 7: [c4, e4, g4, bb4]  → bluesy, wants to resolve
//   minor 7:    [c4, eb4, g4, bb4] → mellow, neo-soul

setcpm(30)

// Compare chord types — same root, different 3rd/7th
note("<[c4,e4,g4] [c4,eb4,g4] [c4,eb4,gb4] [c4,e4,gs4]>")
  .sound("piano").slow(2)
// Major → Minor → Diminished → Augmented

// --- 7th chord colors ---
// note("<[c4,e4,g4,b4] [c4,eb4,g4,bb4] [c4,e4,g4,bb4]>")
//   .sound("piano").slow(2).room(0.4)
// Maj7 → min7 → dom7

// --- ARPEGGIO: play chord notes in sequence ---
// note("c4 e4 g4 b4 g4 e4 c4 ~").sound("piano").slow(2)


// ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
// 5. CHORD ALTERNATION WITH < >
// ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
//
//   note("<chord1 chord2 chord3>")   → one chord per cycle, rotating
//   note("<chord1 chord2>").slow(2)  → one chord per 2 cycles
//   note("<chord1 chord2>").slow(4)  → one chord per 4 cycles
//
// This is how chord progressions are written in Strudel.
// Combine with bass and melody lines using stack().

setcpm(30)

// I – V – vi – IV in C major (the "pop progression")
note("<[c4,e4,g4] [g3,b3,d4] [a3,c4,e4] [f3,a3,c4]>")
  .sound("piano").slow(2).room(0.3)

// --- With bass following chord roots ---
// stack(
//   note("<c2 g2 a2 f2>").sound("sawtooth").lpf(400).gain(0.7),
//   note("<[c4,e4,g4] [g3,b3,d4] [a3,c4,e4] [f3,a3,c4]>")
//     .sound("piano").slow(2).room(0.3).gain(0.6)
// )

// --- Jazz: ii – V – I with 7th chords ---
// note("<[d4,f4,a4,c5] [g3,b3,d4,f4] [c4,e4,g4,b4]>")
//   .sound("piano").slow(3).room(0.4)


// ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
// 6. CHORD PROGRESSIONS — VOICING GUIDE
// ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
//
// COMMON PROGRESSIONS (Roman numerals = scale degree, uppercase=major, lowercase=minor):
//
//   I – IV – V – I        folk, country, gospel
//     C major:  [c4,e4,g4] → [f3,a3,c4] → [g3,b3,d4] → [c4,e4,g4]
//
//   I – V – vi – IV       "pop progression" — thousands of songs
//     C major:  [c4,e4,g4] → [g3,b3,d4] → [a3,c4,e4] → [f3,a3,c4]
//
//   i – VI – III – VII    cinematic minor
//     A minor:  [a3,c4,e4] → [f3,a3,c4] → [c4,e4,g4] → [g3,b3,d4]
//
//   ii – V – I            jazz cadence (strongest resolution)
//     C major: [d4,f4,a4] → [g3,b3,d4,f4] → [c4,e4,g4,b4]
//
//   I – vi – ii – V       jazz standard ("Autumn Leaves" feel)
//     F major: [f4,a4,e5] → [d4,f4,c5] → [g4,bb4,f5] → [c4,e4,bb4]
//
//   i – III – VII – iv    minor cowboy / rock
//     E minor: [e3,g3,b3] → [g3,b3,d4] → [d3,fs3,a3] → [a3,c4,e4]

setcpm(30)

// Jazz standard: I – vi – ii – V in F major
note("<[f4,a4,e5] [d4,f4,c5] [g4,bb4,f5] [c4,e4,bb4]>")
  .sound("piano").slow(2).room(0.35).gain(0.7)


// ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
// 7. TRANSPOSITION — .add() and .transpose()
// ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
//
//   .add(n)           shift all notes up by n semitones
//   .add(-n)          shift down by n semitones
//   .transpose(n)     same as .add(n) (alias)
//   .add(note("c5"))  shift up to the C5 register (used with n())
//
//   12 semitones = 1 octave
//   Common transpositions:
//     +2  whole step up (C → D)
//     +5  perfect fourth up (C → F)
//     +7  perfect fifth up (C → G)
//    +12  up one octave
//    -12  down one octave

setcpm(30)

// Same pattern, shifted up by a 5th (7 semitones)
note("c4 e4 g4 e4").sound("piano")
// note("c4 e4 g4 e4").sound("piano").add(7)    // now G major
// note("c4 e4 g4 e4").sound("piano").add(-12)  // down an octave

// --- Practical: shift a melody into a higher register ---
// n("0 ~ 3 ~ 2 ~ 4 0").scale("C:minpentatonic").sound("triangle")
//   .add(note("c5"))   // shifts the scale root up to C5 range


// ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
// 8. MIDI NUMBERS
// ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
//
// Every note has a MIDI number. Middle C (C4) = 60. Each semitone = +1.
// Each octave = 12. Formula: MIDI = 60 + (octave - 4) × 12 + degree
//
//   48 = C3    60 = C4    72 = C5    84 = C6
//   50 = D3    62 = D4    64 = E4    65 = F4
//   67 = G4    69 = A4    71 = B4    70 = Bb4
//
// note() accepts MIDI numbers directly:

setcpm(30)
note("60 62 64 65 67 65 64 62").sound("piano").slow(2)

// note("60 63 67").sound("piano")    // C4 Eb4 G4 = C minor chord
// note("48 55 60 64 67").sound("piano")  // C3 G3 C4 E4 G4 = wide voicing


// ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
// 9. RESTS, RHYTHM INSIDE NOTE PATTERNS
// ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
//
// All mini-notation operators work inside note() and n() strings:
//   ~          rest / silence
//   *n         repeat note n times
//   [a b]      subdivide slot
//   <a b>      alternate notes each cycle
//   /n         play once every n cycles

setcpm(30)

// Rests shape the rhythm of a melody
note("c5 ~ eb5 ~ g4 bb4 ~ c5  ~ ~ g4 ~ f4 ~ eb4 ~")
  .sound("piano").slow(2).room(0.3)

// --- Repeated note (tremolo-like) ---
// note("c4*4 e4*2 g4*4").sound("piano")

// --- Alternating pitch within a slot ---
// note("c4 <e4 g4> c4 <e4 g4>").sound("piano")

// --- Subdivision for grace notes ---
// note("[c4 d4] e4 [f4 e4] d4").sound("piano").slow(2)

// --- Full melody example with drums ---
// stack(
//   s("bd ~ sd ~"),
//   s("hh*8").gain(0.35),
//   n("0 ~ 2 ~ 4 3 2 0").scale("C:minor").sound("piano")
//     .slow(2).room(0.3).gain(0.6)
// )
